Monitor)\n2. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` — running ✅ (DTLX 5p Monitor)\n3. `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134` — done ✅\n\n\n4. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` — running ✅ (Agent Status to Lead)\n5. `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5163901258` — running ✅\n6. `agent:master-orchestrator:main` — done ✅\n7. `agent:master-orchestrator:subagent:c2d275a5-d70a-4775-a268-fecf4708f133` — done ✅\n8. `agent:planner:subagent:63bb70ce-b5f3-48d0-a236`\n\nNow I'm reviewing the current state against the baseline from 20:29 UTC to identify what's changed. The cron:ed2d0b5d process is still running and stable, but I'm noticing the telegram:direct:6053576134 session has ended since the last check, which is a notable transition in the system state. I need to recalibrate my baseline expectations—the heartbeat-state.json file is tracking four sessions that were active at 20:29 UTC, but I'm now comparing against a different time window where only three of those are still running, and I should account for the fact that the current session itself is part of this runtime environment. Looking at the session status more carefully, the main branch ended around 19:28 UTC which aligns with the stored state, but I'm noticing the telegram group session was already marked as stale in the baseline and remains unchanged. Let me cross-check the child sessions from the parent cron session to see if there are any active sub-agents I should account for.\n\nComparing the heartbeat timestamps across runs, the cron:ed2d0b5d process has progressed from 26 minutes to 96 minutes of runtime since the baseline, which is just the normal passage of time. The core session state hasn't shifted—no new zombies spawned, no blockers emerged, and the pipeline health remains solid. There are a couple of additional cron processes that started in this current timeframe.\n\nI'm realizing I need to be more careful about what the baseline actually represents. The heartbeat-state.json was last updated at 20:29 UTC and captures a snapshot of sessions at that moment. Sessions that existed in that baseline and are still running haven't fundamentally changed in terms of their status, even though their runtime has extended. The question isn't whether they've been running longer, but whether their status or existence has shifted. Looking at the current session list, all four tracked sessions from the baseline are still running as they were at 20:29 UTC.\n\nThe new cron processes are separate from this comparison—they're independent from the baseline. So I'm checking: did any of the originally tracked sessions change status or die? No. Did any new sessions that should be tracked appear? Looking at the child sessions, the planner and master-orchestrator subagents are all showing as done, which matches what I'd expect from the baseline.\n\nNow I'm reviewing the current state across all the active sessions. The cron jobs are all running as expected—the QLHV monitor, DTLX monitor, and agent status check are all stable. The telegram group is also running but hasn't had activity in about 17 minutes, which is a bit stale but not alarming. The main session ended around 20 minutes ago, which is fine since it was just a heartbeat check. So everything looks healthy and consistent with the baseline—no changes to report."},{"type":"text","text":"Silent. All critical sessions remain stable vs. stored baseline (20:29 UTC):\n\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` ✅ running (QLHV 5p — ~97m, expected long-running)\n- `cron:6f3323ef` ✅ running (DTLX 5p — stable)\n- `cron:e7885813` ✅ running (Agent Status — stable)\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258` ✅ running (stale ~17m, known)\n- `main` ✅ done (ended ~19:28 UTC — expected)\n- All child subagents: done (confirmed clean)\n\nNo failures. No blockers. Pipeline: HEALTHY."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":29375,"output":10